\f0\b \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Graduate school advice that will help you get there\
\
\pard\tx360\pardeftab720\li360\fi-360\ri0\sl360\slmult1
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 \ulnone Be persistent with your research.  Many of your papers will get rejected (some may get rejected several times).  Don\'d5t let this discourage you, it happens to most everyone.  Take the reviewers\'d5 comments for what they are worth, some will be serious comments, some will be misinformed, and some will simply be the reviewers being impatient jerks.  A rejection from a journal is not a reflection on you or the science.  Be persistent.  If you think you can adequately address the criticisms raised by the reviewers, it is okay to call or e-mail the editor (be nice) and ask if s/he\'d5d consider another look (explain your issues).
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Sell yourself high.  This means sending your work to the best journals.  This also means a higher probability of rejection.  However, the best journals will never publish your work unless you send it to them.  Model your papers after papers on similar topics in those journals.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Give talks-- two a year and at least one at national/international meetings once you have data.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Invite seminar speakers!  Think of heros and potential post-doc advisors and invite them.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Learn the academic industry: how to review papers, grants, etc. ask your major professor about this and have him/her to let you in on reviews etc.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Do collaborative projects with students and faculty who aren\'d5t in your lab.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Do side projects not directly linked to your thesis which expand your breadth, but don\'d5t spread yourself too thin.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone The most important thing you will take with you to a job interview is a solid 45 minute talk that is a cohesive, complete story.  Thus, above all else, some of your research projects must converge on a story that does not require jumping around or switching gears!
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Publish in the general journals but also in the specialized journals corresponding to what you want to be: entomology journals if you want to be an entomologist, conservation journals if you want a conservation biology position.  Try to have a mix of thick papers (long and dense, few people may ever read these, but they are critical to show you can do solid work) and slim papers (papers that will actually get read, have some flashiness, but may not be as overwhelmingly solid).
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Write a review/synthesis paper\'d1these are hard to get published as graduate students because nobody knows you, but you often will have all the current papers in an emerging area because of your dissertation project--- put them together and synthesize.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Use the \'d2scan-doc\'d3 or \'d2weekly update\'d3 function from the library to keep up on the literature in your field.  This will send you the latest articles based on your search criteria (author name, key word, title word, etc) every week (including abstracts).  In addition, sign of up for the free table-of-contents alerts from the major journals in your field\'c9 this will help you stay on top of the literature,
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Pay membership dues and subscribe to the hard copy for one of the major society journals (Ecology, Am Nat, Evolution) \'c9 carry around the paper copy in your backpack until you\'d5ve at least read most of the abstracts.  The guilt of getting the paper copy in your mailbox is a good thing.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Do something so that you can say you taught your own course\'d1even if the pay is non-existent.  Look into doing a hybrid seminar course where you give 10 lectures and have 20 hours of discussion (or whatever)--- this will be a lot less work than a real lecture course, but is more than a seminar--- you will get credit later on in the process for teaching a course yourself.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Publish soon.  Try and have a good paper submitted every year starting as early as you can, but not later than your third year.
\f0\b \ul \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \ulnone Move institutions between degrees and travel while at your current place.  Different supervisors, graduate programs, departments, etc. all offer slightly different perspectives.  It is important for scientists to interact with different groups and to reinvent themselves in different environments to stay sharp. It will also be handy to have referees from different institutions.\
