\cf0 Once you get the offer, you hold all of the cards.  Talk to lots of experienced people about negotiating\'d1almost everybody feels like they could have done a better job.  Do not agree to stuff you are not prepared to agree to at first.  It is always okay to say, you will need to think about that.  Or let me get back to you on that.  Once you agree to anything it is hard to take it back\'c9 There may be several phone calls, several paid re-visits, and several versions of the written offer before you sign.  Get things that are important to you in writing.  Ask for things you need- don\'d5t be embarrassed.  If you don\'d5t ask you won\'d5t get it, and you definitely won\'d5t get it later.  It is important to figure out if somethings are non-negotiable because the department\'d5s hands are tied.  On the one hand, everything is negotiable, on the other hand, if the department\'d5s building is small and full, and everybody essentially has the same amount of space, chances are that you will not be able to negotiate more space.  There are two important aspects to this recognition: first, picking your battles in terms of things that you really want and can get, and 2\super nd\nosupersub , not pissing off the rest of the faculty or chair.  You will get a sense of what is possible and what is impossible, push hard, but not too hard.\
